\section{Introduction}
The purpose of this note is to describe a small modal type theory with internalized parametricity.
Internalized parametricity means we should have {\em internal} witnesses of ``free theorems''. For example,
if we have a polymorphic function
\[ q : (X : \rtype) \to X \to X \]
then there should be a proof, in the type theory itself, that $q$ is the identity function.

There are lots of other type theories for internalized parametricity. This might even be a special case of one of the existing ones.
Some considerations that intentionally constrain this one:
\begin{itemize}
\item It avoids an explicit interval type.
\item It does not require cubical primitives.
\item It does not handle iterated internalized parametricity.
\item It does not definitionally `bake in' the meaning of parametricity for each type former. Instead,
the fact that a function belongs to the relation if it preserves related things is a {\em theorem} of the system.
\item The syntax is split into two {\em levels}, called $\wid{\hbox{wide}}$ and $\nar{\hbox{narrow}}$.
Wide things are things `equipped with parametricity data', and narrow things are those without.
\item The theory is modal; Hypotheses in the context may exist at various modes.
\item There are only three novel type constructors compared to normal dependent type theory.
\end{itemize}


\section{Language}


%% The type theory is modal and has two levels, called $\wid{\hbox{wide}}$ and $\nar{\hbox{narrow}}$.

%% One pervasive intuition that is helpful to lean on is that we are, in this theory,
%% ``programming in the presheaf category $\rtype^{\bf 2}$'', where $\bf 2$ is the category
%% with two objects and one trivial morphism.


In both levels, we have several sorts of variables in the context.
Variables may be ordinary $x : \wid A$, strong $x :: \wid A$, or weak $x \div \nar A$.



\[\begin{tabular}{rccl}
 Wide Contexts&$\wid \Gamma$&$::=$&$\cdot  \celse \wid\Gamma, x :: \wid A \celse \wid\Gamma, x \div \nar A  \celse \wid \Gamma, x : \wid A$\\
  Narrow Contexts&$\nar\Gamma$&$::=$&$\cdot \celse \nar \Gamma, x :: \wid A\celse \nar \Gamma, x \div \nar A  $\\
  Wide Types&$\wid A$&$::=$&$\cdots
 \celse \gg (x : \nar A) . \nar B
 \celse \wipe \nar A
%  \celse \dia {\nar A}
$\\
  Narrow Types&$\nar A$&$::=$&$\cdots
  \celse \pp {\nar M} {\wid A}
$\\
Wide  Terms&$\wid M$&$::=$&$\cdots
\celse \epair{\nar M }{\nar N}
\celse \bglue(\nar M, \nar P)
$\\
Narrow  Terms&$\nar M$&$::=$&$\cdots
\celse \{ \wid M \}
